      "died_place": "Nottingham",
      "bio": "Samuel Waite Johnson (b. 14 October 1831, Bramley, Yorkshire; d. 14 January 1912, Nottingham) was one of the foremost locomotive designers of the steam age. He served as Locomotive Superintendent and Chief Mechanical Engineer of the Midland Railway Company. His most celebrated designs include the Midland Single (the 'Spinner'), a series of elegant single-driver express locomotives with 7-foot driving wheels that became icons of Victorian railway engineering. He lived at 27 Lenton Road (Lenton House by 1911) throughout the census period, and was listed as Chief Mechanical Engineer of the Midland Railway Company in 1901.",
